## Subject-Wise Summer Goals for Class 10
### Mathematics
Summer Goal: Cover Number Systems, Polynomials, and Pair of Linear Equations.
These three chapters are the foundation for everything that follows in Class 10 Maths. Quadratics, Triangles, and Arithmetic Progressions all build on concepts introduced here. A shaky base in summer = a stressful November.
Action Plan:

Revise Class 9 Algebra and Coordinate Geometry first (1 week)
Solve every NCERT exercise — no skipping, no selective practice
Start a "silly mistakes" notebook: log every repeated error so you stop making it


Habit Hack: Do Maths first thing in the morning. Even 45 minutes at 7 AM = 45+ hours of solid practice before school reopens.


### Science
Summer Goal: Complete Chemical Reactions & Equations (Chemistry) + Life Processes (Biology).
Science in Class 10 is really three subjects — Physics, Chemistry, Biology. Students who treat it as "one subject" always lose marks in at least one area. Summer is your chance to go slowly, read deeply, and actually understand mechanisms instead of memorising them.
Action Plan:

Make a handwritten formula + reaction chart for Chemistry (stick it on your wall)
Draw and label Biology diagrams daily — heart, nephron, reflex arc, stomata
Watch one NCERT-based concept video before reading the textbook chapter — it primes your brain


### Social Science (SST)
Summer Goal: Finish History Chapter 1 (Rise of Nationalism in Europe) + Geography Chapter 1 (Resources and Development).
SST has the highest word-count in the Class 10 syllabus — and the most marks available if you study it the right way. Most students ignore it in summer and spend October regretting it.
Action Plan:

Read each chapter like a story, not a list of facts to memorise
Make a 1-page mind map per chapter as you finish it
Revise Class 9 SST basics (Democratic Politics, Economics) — Class 10 builds directly on them


### English
Summer Goal: Master grammar fundamentals + read First Flight and Footprints without Feet once through.
English is where 85% students become 95% students — or don't. Grammar (tenses, voices, reported speech, modals) is fully predictable in CBSE exams and can be mastered in 3–4 focused weeks.
Action Plan:

20 minutes of grammar practice daily using CBSE sample papers (2024–25)
Read 1 story or poem per day — understand theme, not just plot
Keep a vocabulary journal: 5 new words per day from your reading


### Hindi
Summer Goal: Read Kshitij and Kritika prose chapters once + revise vyakaran basics.
Hindi grammar — samasa, alankar, ras, sangya, sarvnaam — is highly predictable in CBSE papers. Master these in summer and you walk into the Hindi exam with 20+ marks already locked in.

A Daily Routine That Actually Fits Summer Vacation
This is a 4-hour plan. It leaves you plenty of time for rest, sports, and screen time — while still building serious momentum.
| Time | Activity |
