## 5 Habit Hacks Toppers Actually Use

* The 2-Minute Rule: If a chapter feels overwhelming, commit to just 2 minutes. You'll almost always keep going once you've started.

* Habit stacking: Study immediately after brushing your teeth in the morning. Your brain starts associating the routine — and getting into focus becomes automatic.

* Weekly Sunday Review: Spend 30 minutes every Sunday reviewing what you covered that week. This single habit can boost long-term retention by up to 40%.

* Phone in another room: Not silent. Not face-down. Another room entirely. Distraction-free study is measurably 2x more effective per hour.

* 8 hours of sleep — non-negotiable: Memory consolidation happens during sleep. Cutting sleep to study more is counterproductive. Your brain needs the downtime to retain what you learnt.


## Frequently Asked Questions
> **Q: How many hours should a Class 10 student study in summer vacation?**
4–5 focused hours per day is the sweet spot. Quality beats quantity — 4 distraction-free hours outperforms 8 unfocused ones every time.

> **Q: Which subject should I focus on most in summer before Class 10?**
Maths and Science need the most time because they demand conceptual practice. Prioritise these in the morning. SST and English can be covered in shorter afternoon sessions.

> **Q: Is it okay to enjoy summer vacation as a Class 10 student?**
Yes — and it's essential. Rest isn't an obstacle to prep; it's part of it. A burnt-out student in November scores worse than a rested one who studied 4 consistent hours in May.

